\f2\b\fs56 \cf2 Seeing the forest and the trees\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li7600\fi-7600\ri7600\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 Anthropic Interviewer asked each interviewee a set list of questions about what they want and don\'92t want from AI, then adapted follow-up questions based on responses. This approach bridges the typical tradeoff in qualitative research between depth and volume, and allows us to collect rich, open-ended interviews at a very large scale.\cb1 \
\cb3 To make sense of this huge amount of information, we built Claude-powered classifiers that categorized each conversation across a range of dimensions\'97what people want from AI, whether they\'92re getting what they want, what they fear, what they do for a living (if mentioned), and their sentiment about AI overall. \'93What people want from AI\'94 was classified into a single primary category per respondent, while concerns were multi-label\'97a single interview could receive multiple codes, since respondents tended to articulate several distinct worries rather than one.\cb1 \
\cb3 We also used Claude to pull out representative quotes. Before choosing to participate, users were informed their responses would be used for research, and that Anthropic might publish responses with personally identifying information removed in findings. All responses were de-identified before being analyzed by a small team of researchers at Anthropic, and quotes selected for publication underwent further manual review for removal of any potentially identifying details, to help protect the privacy and public anonymity of interviewees. Answers were reflective of AI usage broadly (i.e. not just Claude), though we redacted names of other AI products.\cb1 \
\
\cb3 The\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://cdn.sanity.io/files/4zrzovbb/website/99156863ed4a812569fe00a2adfb1c93f7e5a911.pdf"}}{\fldrslt \ul Appendix}}\'a0describes our methods in more detail, as well as limitations and some additional analysis.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li7600\fi-7600\ri7600\partightenfactor0

