\f0\b0 \cf7 \cb3 What respondents most wanted from AI, classified by Claude from their open-ended answers to "If you could wave a magic wand, what would AI do for you?" 1% of respondents did not articulate a vision. Hover to see example quotes.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li7600\fi-7600\ri7600\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 AI is used heavily for work, and so it\'92s perhaps unsurprising that the largest group of people (19%) sought \'93professional excellence\'94\'97wanting AI to handle mundane tasks so they can focus on strategic, higher-level problems. Another 9% envisioned AI as an entrepreneurial partner to help them build and scale businesses.\cb1 \
\cb3 Many others similarly started the interview talking about productivity, but after Anthropic Interviewer asked about their underlying hope behind it\'97what realizing this vision would enable for them\'97other priorities surfaced. It wasn\'92t about doing better work, but increasing their quality of life outside of it. Using AI to automate e-mails became, in actuality, a desire to spend more time with family.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li7350\fi-7350\ri7350\sa340\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 \strokec10 \'93With AI I can be more efficient at work... last Tuesday it allowed me to cook with my mother instead of finishing tasks.\'94
\f2\b\fs26 \cf7 \cb1 \strokec7 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf7 \cb3 WHITE COLLAR WORKER, COLOMBIA\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li7350\fi-7350\ri7350\sa340\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec10 \'93I want to use less brain power on client problems... have time to read more books.\'94
\f2\b\fs26 \cf7 \cb1 \strokec7 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf7 \cb3 FREELANCER, JAPAN\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li7600\fi-7600\ri7600\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs34 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 Overall, 11% of people saw AI\'92s productivity benefits as ultimately a way to free up time for personal relationships and leisure, while 10% took that logic farther, seeking to use AI to gain financial independence. Many of the people grouped into the \'93life management\'94 category (14%) also wanted AI to help them manage the logistics and administrative burden of modern life\'92s quotidian tasks. In particular, many people with executive function challenges described AI as especially helpful for managing focus and organization\'97acting as external scaffolding for planning, memory, and task follow-through. Across all these groups, the unifying ask was for AI to help them live better, more enjoyable lives.\cb1 \
\
\cb3 \'93Personal transformation\'94\'97using AI to help one grow or improve their wellbeing as a person\'97also appeared frequently (14%). Within this category, the desires were diverse, ranging from cognitive partnership and collaboration (24%), to support with mental health (21%) or physical health (8%), and even romantic connection with AI (5%).\cb1 \
\cb3 The nine clusters may look disparate, but they are underpinned by recognizably human desires. Roughly a third of visions are about making room for life\'97more time, money, mental bandwidth\'97by using AI to alleviate current burdens. Another quarter revolves around using AI to help people do better, more fulfilling work (not escaping work, but getting more out of it). About a fifth are about becoming someone better\'97learning, healing, growing. A smaller share want to make something (\'93creative expression\'94) or fix the world (\'93societal transformation\'94).\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \cb3 Those that wanted societal transformation from AI often cited a vision for healthcare\'97people wanted AI to detect cancer earlier, accelerate drug discovery, or enable broad access. Often these desires stemmed from personal experience of losing family members, living with chronic illness, or watching loved ones receive wrong or delayed diagnoses. Transformation in the form of education came next. Respondents in low and middle income countries were quick to cite the possibility that AI might break the association between educational quality and wealth. They pointed to teacher shortages in their countries, or the prohibitive cost of private tutors. Others hoped that AI would, for example, free people from drudgery, help repair broken institutions, or address global crises.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li7600\fi-7600\ri7600\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs56 \cf2 \cb3 Are people getting what they want?\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li7600\fi-7600\ri7600\partightenfactor0

